                            &#10149; Read on
                        </a>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">After liberation: the sisters return to Hungary</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    After the liberation near Tröbitz, the sisters stayed in the village for a while. Zsuzsa Merényi fell ill 
                    with typhoid fever there and was cared for by Lea Merényi until she recovered. Unlike many other Hungarians, 
                    the sisters returned to their home country after the liberation. However, the family’s home in Budapest was 
                    already occupied by other people, so within Hungary Lea Merényi initially moved in with her aunt Delora. 
                    After her return, Lea Merényi worked for the Hungarian Railway Company (MAV) for about a year, later as a 
                    German teacher, retiring in the 1970s.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Following her return, Zsuzsa Merényi married and together with her husband, founded the Budapest Ballet Academy, 
                    where she also gave lessons.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Only upon their return did the sisters learn that their mother had perished in the ghetto in Budapest. 
                    The search for their brother, their grandparents from Wuppertal-Barmen, and other relatives was unsuccessful. 
                    Their brother Istvan (Stefan) had died in Bergen-Belsen at the beginning of 1945, just a few yards away from 
                    the sisters – information that never reached them during their lifetime.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Zsuzsa Merényi passed away on August 15, 1990, Lea 17 years later, on December 31, 2007 in Hungary.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="mt-4">Source situation</h3>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <p>
                    These biographies are primarily based on the stories and recollections of Lea Merényi, which she processed 
                    in two interviews and eyewitness accounts with the Bergen-Belsen Memorial. Since 1999, video interviews 
                    have been conducted with the survivors of the concentration and prisoner-of-war camp, as well as other 
                    contemporary witnesses, toward the scholarly, educational, and museum work of the memorial on site. These 
                    memoirs enable the survivors to put their own narrative about the Shoah in a historical context and actively 
                    shape the work of the Memorial. In Lea Merényi’s case, the interview also enabled her to talk about her 
                    experiences, as she had made an agreement with her sister not to speak about the past. Her subjective 
                    descriptions of her experiences were supplemented by information from an interview with Zsuzsa Merényi on 
                    April 20, 1990<sup><a href="#endnote9" id="footnote9">9</a></sup> as well as key historical data, primarily 
                    based on the catalog of the exhibition at the Bergen-Belsen Memorial. In addition, diary entries and drawings 
                    by Zsuzsa Merényi exist. 
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

